 ### 7.1 Option 1: By building and installing a system extension (`systemd-sysext`)
 
-> This option works best if you want to temporarily and quickly deploy your changes to your local workstation. No reboot is required to see your changes in action. The one component that can't be iterated on with system extensions is the kernel — for that, use the [`systemd-sysupdate` option](#72-option-2-by-building-serving-and-updating-from-a-local-sysupdate-repository-systemd-sysupdate) instead.
+> This option works best if you want to temporarily and quickly deploy your changes to your local workstation or a remote machine. No reboot is required to see your changes in action. The one component that can't be iterated on with system extensions is the kernel — for that, use the [`systemd-sysupdate` option](#72-option-2-by-building-serving-and-updating-from-a-local-sysupdate-repository-systemd-sysupdate) instead.
 
 > While this works for any of the included apps too, not just system components, iterating on apps directly using Flatpak via for example [GNOME Builder](https://apps.gnome.org/Builder/) or [Foundry](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/foundry) is preferred.
 
@@ -184,9 +184,30 @@ $ run0 rm /var/lib/extensions/zz-gnome-control-center.raw
 $ run0 systemd-sysext refresh
 ```
 
+On a remote workstation or VM, deploy the system extension by running the following:
+
+```shell
+$ scp zz-gnome-control-center.sysext.raw user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip:/tmp/
+$ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 sysext-add --persistent /tmp/zz-gnome-control-center.sysext.raw
+$ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 systemd-sysext refresh
+```
+
+If the component includes systemd units, reload the daemon by running the following:
+
+```shell
+$ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 systemctl daemon-reload
+```
+
+To remove the system extension from a remote workstation or VM, run the following:
+
+```shell
+$ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 rm /var/lib/extensions/zz-gnome-control-center.raw
+$ ssh user@remote-workstation-hostname-or-ip run0 systemd-sysext refresh
+```
+
 ### 7.2 Option 2: By building, serving and updating from a local sysupdate repository (`systemd-sysupdate`)
 
-> This option works best if you want to permanently deploy your changes to your local workstation, or if you want to deploy to a VM or a different workstation. A reboot is required to see your changes in action. Unlike with the [`systemd-sysext` option](#71-option-1-by-building-and-installing-a-system-extension-systemd-sysext), this option can be used to iterate on the kernel.
